[Aim 1] - creating a recommendation system for consumers based on their genres of interest

Columns that will interest consumers: Director, Cast, Production Company, Genre, Vote_Count

The Director and Main Cast are important as consumers often have favorite directors and actors whose work they actively seek out. Additionally, the Production Company can impact consumer interest, especially if known for producing high-quality films which contributes in terms of brand recognition. High vote counts generally indicate a movieâs popularity and suggest a larger audience engagement which will assist in selecting quality movies for recommendations. Finally, Genre is a requirement, as it helps match movies to consumersâ specific genre preferences.

[Aim 2] - identifying focus areas for future directors

Columns that will interest consumers: budget, release_date, production company, vote_average and revenue

Similarly, Production company might play an important role in contributing to a filmâs success and revenue. Moreover, understanding the relationship between budget and revenue can guide directors in making cost-effective decisions that still yield high returns. Release Date helps identify the time periods that attracts the most consumers. Finally, Vote Average and Revenue is a requirement as they are the main focus components in the aim.

Modifications made

NA values can cause the algorithm to generate skewed or less meaningful association rules. Given the importance of âMain Castâ, âGenreâ and âVote Countâ in Aim 1 and âProduction Companyâ, âBudgetâ, âVote Averageâ, âRevenueâ in Aim 2 , itâs crucial to remove any rows with NA or 0 values in these columns to ensure the Apriori algorithm can function properly and generate meaningful associations.

NA values in columns like âProduction Countryâ and âRun Timeâ can be ignored since they are not relevant to the analysis goals for Aim 1 and Aim 2. For âMain Castsâ which are 0, they are treated as N/A and are to be removed later on in Aim 1 itself when converting to long format.

# Replace 0 values in Main Cast with 0
Master_Dataset$main_cast_1[Master_Dataset$main_cast_1 == 0] <- NA
Master_Dataset$main_cast_2[Master_Dataset$main_cast_2 == 0] <- NA
Master_Dataset$main_cast_3[Master_Dataset$main_cast_3 == 0] <- NA

# Remove rows with NA or 0 values in specified columns
Master_Dataset <- Master_Dataset %>%
  filter(
    # Aim 1 variables
    Genres != 'NA',
    !is.na(vote_count) & vote_count != 0,
    # Aim 2 variables
    !is.na(productioncompany),
    budget != 0,
    !is.na(vote_average) & vote_average != 0,
    !is.na(revenue) & revenue != 0,
  )

Lastly, columns of character data types have single quotation marks in each value. We can clean the data to standardize the format.

# Replace single quotation marks with empty strings
Master_Dataset$director <- gsub("'", "", Master_Dataset$director)
Master_Dataset$main_cast_1 <- gsub("'", "", Master_Dataset$main_cast_1)
Master_Dataset$main_cast_2 <- gsub("'", "", Master_Dataset$main_cast_2)
Master_Dataset$main_cast_3 <- gsub("'", "", Master_Dataset$main_cast_3)
Master_Dataset$productioncompany <- gsub("'", "", Master_Dataset$productioncompany)
Master_Dataset$productioncountry <- gsub("'", "", Master_Dataset$productioncountry)
Master_Dataset$Genres <- gsub("'", "", Master_Dataset$Genres)

Stage 3: Data Preparation for Apriori for Assignment Aim 1

The steps for the conversion from dataset to transactional format includes identifying the transactional Items, converting interval values to percentiles, filter and create sets of transactional data.

Step 1 - Identifying the transactional items

Master_Dataset_Aim1 <- Master_Dataset[, c("id", "main_cast_1" , "main_cast_2" , "main_cast_3" ,"Genres", "vote_count")]

To create an effective recommendation system for consumers, Main Cast is selected as a key dimension as it aligns with audience preferences and helps in recommending films featuring actors known for their consistent performance and genre choices which improves the overall consumer experience. In addition, Vote Count is also selected as a variable to recommend movies of good quality to consumers.

Step 2 - Converting interval values to percentile

# Function to categorize columns into Low, Medium and High
categorize_LMH <- function(column) {
  
  # Calculate percentiles
  percentiles <- quantile(column, probs = c(0.33, 0.67))
  
  cut(column,
      breaks = c(-Inf, percentiles, Inf),
      labels = c("Low", "Medium", "High"),
      right = TRUE)
}

# Categorize Vote average into Low and High
Master_Dataset_Aim1$vote_count <- as.numeric(Master_Dataset_Aim1$vote_count)
Master_Dataset_Aim1$vote_count <- categorize_LMH(Master_Dataset_Aim1$vote_count)

Vote Count is categorized into three distinct categories: Low, Medium & High using 33rd and 67th percentiles. It accommodates different consumer interests, as some may prefer well-received films with high ratings, while others may explore films with polarizing appeal in lower-rated categories. For recommending content, focusing on high and medium vote counts ensures that we highlight movies with large audiences and quality, while filtering out those with lower ratings. Thereby improving the likelihood of attracting more viewers and ensuring the most promising recommendations.

Step 3 - Filter and create sets of transactional data

The main focus of genres are Fantasy, Drama and Action. Therefore, 3 sets of transactional data will be created.

# Filtering of rows to include those of interest

Stage 4: Genre Analysis Assignment Aim 1

Over the course of their careers, actors often become reliable markers for film quality and specific genres, especially if they have consistently chosen similar roles. As highlighted by Liu et al.Â (2014), evidence shows that âconsistentâ stars are more successful in attracting viewers. This consistency creates strong audience expectations and trust in certain actorsâ work. Therefore, after consideration, for Aim 1, the only variable of focus is the Main Cast.

Step 2 - Converting interval values to percentile

Revenue tends to have a more straightforward distribution, where the difference between low and high revenue is significant. By focusing on just two categories, the analysis can be simplified, which is particularly important since revenue is the target variable of interest analyzed in the Apriori algorithm. This approach allows for clearer insights into how other factors like production company are associated with either high or low revenue, without the potential noise that might come from a middle category that could blur these relationships. The same reasoning can be applied to budget as well.

For Vote Count, it can be referred to in Step 2 of Stage 3.

Since Vote Average operates on a smaller scale, categorizing it allows us to focus on selecting and analyzing the qualities of only the best-rated films. By narrowing down to the highest-rated movies, directors can gain deeper insights into what truly resonates with audiences at the top tier. This categorization can help directors tailor future projects to align more closely with audience preferences, enabling them to make better decisions.

# Function to categorize columns into Low, Medium and High
categorize_LMH <- function(column) {
  
  # Calculate percentiles
  percentiles <- quantile(column, probs = c(0.33, 0.67))
  
  cut(column,
      breaks = c(-Inf, percentiles, Inf),
      labels = c("Low", "Medium", "High"),
      right = TRUE)
}

# Function to categorize columns into Low and High
categorize_LH <- function(column) {
  
  # Calculate the 50th percentile
  median_value <- quantile(column, probs = 0.5)
  
  cut(column,
      breaks = c(-Inf, median_value, Inf),
      labels = c("Low", "High"),
      right = TRUE)
}

# Categorize Vote Average to Low, Medium and High
Master_Dataset_Aim2$vote_average <- as.numeric(Master_Dataset_Aim2$vote_average)
Master_Dataset_Aim2$vote_average <- categorize_LMH(Master_Dataset_Aim2$vote_average)

# Categorize Revenue to Low and High
Master_Dataset_Aim2$revenue <- as.numeric(Master_Dataset_Aim2$revenue)
Master_Dataset_Aim2$revenue <- categorize_LH(Master_Dataset_Aim2$revenue)

# Categorize Budget to Low and High
Master_Dataset_Aim2$budget <- as.numeric(Master_Dataset_Aim2$budget)
Master_Dataset_Aim2$budget <- categorize_LH(Master_Dataset_Aim2$budget)

To create the recommendation system for directors with vote average and revenue as the target interests, two sets of transactional data will be created namely high vote averages and high revenue. # Filtering of rows to include those of interest

Stage 7: Conclusion

For consumers interested in Fantasy, consider exploring movies featuring Gene Hackman or Bruce Willis, and also delve into the Family and Adventure genres. Consumers interested in Drama genres, can look into movies starring Robert De Niro or Keanu Reeves and also consider Romance and Thriller genres. For fans of Action, look for movies with Catherine Deneuve or Gene Hackman, and consider the Adventure and Thriller genres.

Directors aiming to optimize their filmâs performance should consider releasing their projects towards the end of the year, particularly in December and September, as these months are linked to higher vote averages. For directors aiming to maximize revenue, focusing on high-budget productions and timing releases in December, June, or July can be more effective. Additionally, collaborating with successful production companies identified for their revenue generation like Paramount Pictures and Universal Pictures could further enhance revenue.
